I will probably see it multiple times and then buy it after it comes out. Thank you whoever made this and everyone who had a part in making this. text: I am so excited for this movie!!! I had this book read aloud to me in 4th grade (I'm going into 9th now) and I fell in love with it. I have since read the book over 10 times, read all three side character stories, read 1 quote from 365 Days of Wonder every day for a year, and even met the author. I have done countless projects on this book. Every teacher I have tells me that this is too easy as I am reading on a 12th grade reading level which is true, but I love it so much that I read it in my free time. It sends a great message, and I wish it was a middle school requirement across the country. When this movie comes out fellow Wonder fans and I will be in the theaters watching! I hope teachers continue to read and inspire other teachers to read this to students because as a student who once had it read aloud, I can tell you first hand that it does make a difference! Remember, "When given the choice between being right and being kind, chose kind." The fact that I remember that quote and think about it on a daily basis nearly 5 years after the first time I hear Wonder shows I am just one kid among many more that this book has inspired!

text: When my daughter ran in my room screaming about seeing this trailer today (it's our favorite book) I got so excited; until I saw the trailer. Now I just feel completely let down and disappointed. First of all, the actor who plays Aggie hardly looks like he has a facial-cranial deformity- so, basically, terrible make-up job, does not drive the point home about how severe Aggie's deformities are in the book. But, the fact that it is a make-up job just sends a terrible message to children with these deformities. A child with Treacher-Collins syndrome should have been cast as Aggie; to children with facial deformities this just sends the message that they are still not good enough- that their deformities are still too severe for them to be cast in a movie and that even a mask has to be watered down to be good enough for the public to sympathize. This is just shameful.
